## 6. Compile Stage Specification

The compile stage reads the clean intermediate CSV and renders the HTML
email. It never modifies data. It never re-validates dates. It never writes
any file except the final HTML output.

### 6.1 Link Safety Pipeline

This is the most critical correctness requirement for Zoho compatibility.
The order of operations is fixed and must never be reversed:

```
Step 1: protect_markdown_links()
        Temporarily replace [label](url) with non-HTML placeholders
        so the escape step cannot corrupt bracket/paren syntax.

Step 2: html.escape()
        Escape all HTML special characters in the text.
        This runs AFTER protect, so markdown link syntax is safe.

Step 3: linkify_escaped_text()
        Convert bare URLs and bare emails in the now-HTML-escaped text
        into proper <a> tags. This operates on HTML-safe text only.

Step 4: restore_markdown_links()
        Replace the placeholders from Step 1 with proper <a> tags,
        using the protected label and URL.
```

**Why this order matters:** If you escape after linkifying, the `<a href=`
tags you just created get their angle brackets escaped into `&lt;a href=`.
If you linkify before protecting, a markdown link like `[click here](https://x.com)`
gets its parentheses and brackets consumed by the linkifier before the
markdown renderer sees them.

**MARKDOWN_LINK_RE** must handle both `https://` and `mailto:` targets:

```python
MARKDOWN_LINK_RE = re.compile(
    r'\[([^\[\]]+)\]\(((?:https?://|mailto:)[^)]+)\)'
)
```

**Trailing punctuation stripping:** When linkifying bare URLs, the `href`
must not include trailing punctuation (`.`, `,`, `)`, `!`, `?`). Strip
trailing punctuation from the matched URL before writing it into `href`.
The punctuation stays in the visible text at its original position.

### 6.2 Image Rendering

Image fields contain 1–3 pipe-separated filenames. The compiler must:

1. Split on `|` and strip whitespace from each part.
2. Discard any entries beyond `MAX_INLINE_IMAGES = 3` with a `[WARN]`.
3. Normalize each path with `to_web_path()` (see Section 6.7).
4. Render one `<img>` tag wrapped in one `<a>` tag per image.
5. Use the **same normalized path** for both `src` and `href`.
6. Stack multiple images vertically inside one outer table container.

**Correct output for two images:**

```html
<table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"
       style="width:100%; background-color:#efe8dc; border:1px solid #d9cfc0; margin-top:14px;">
  <tr>
    <td style="padding:12px;">
      <a href="Images/photo1.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
         style="display:block; text-decoration:none; margin-bottom:12px;">
        <img src="Images/photo1.jpg"
             alt="[Title of the post] photo 1"
             style="display:block; width:100%; max-width:100%; height:auto;">
      </a>
      <a href="Images/photo2.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
         style="display:block; text-decoration:none;">
        <img src="Images/photo2.jpg"
             alt="[Title of the post] photo 2"
             style="display:block; width:100%; max-width:100%; height:auto;">
      </a>
    </td>
  </tr>
</table>
```

**Alt text:** For a single image, use the post title. For multiple images,
append `photo 1`, `photo 2`, etc. Alt text must always be present.

### 6.3 Body Text Rendering

Body text from the intermediate CSV is plain text with optional light
Markdown. The `render_body()` function transforms it into HTML fragments
using these rules, in order:

| Source pattern | HTML output |
|---|---|
| Blank line (`\n\n`) | Paragraph break — wrap each block in `<p>` |
| `## Heading text` | `<h3 style="...">Heading text</h3>` |
| Line starting with `- `, `* `, or `•` | `<ul><li>` block |
| `[label](https://url)` or `[label](mailto:x)` | `<a href="...">label</a>` |
| Everything else | Inline text within `<p>` |

**Paragraph wrapping is mandatory.** Bare text without `<p>` tags renders
inconsistently across email clients. Every text block between blank lines
must be wrapped.

**No raw HTML passthrough.** Body text must be HTML-escaped before rendering.
The link safety pipeline (Section 6.1) handles the correct order.

### 6.4 Table of Contents

Every bulletin and events output includes a TOC at the top of the email.

**Requirements:**
- Every section heading has a corresponding TOC entry.
- Every TOC entry links to a deterministic anchor (`#section-slug`).
- Anchors are collision-safe: if two entries would produce the same slug,
  append `-2`, `-3`, etc.
- TOC links must land the reader at the **top** of the correct entry —
  not mid-entry.
- Section headings in the body must include the matching `id=` attribute.

**TOC text:**
- Bulletins: "In this Bulletin"
- Events: "In this Events Edition"

**Planned improvement:** Sections with exactly one item should show only
the section heading in the TOC, not the individual item entry. Not yet
implemented — track in punch-list.

### 6.5 Callout Boxes

Both compilers render a callout box at the top and bottom of the email body.

- Default text is hardcoded in the compiler.
- `--callout` and `--bottom-callout` CLI flags override defaults.
- The entrypoint passes these flags through to compile stages only.
- If no override is set, the entrypoint emits a `[REMIND]` before running
  the compiler (see Section 4).
- Callout boxes must always render — they are never optional.

### 6.6 Section Ordering

**Bulletins (fixed order — never reorder except Urgent pins first):**

1. Urgent Bulletins — always first when present
2. Housing Opportunities
3. Swap Market
4. Local Services & Help
5. Community Announcements

The `group_rows()` function must produce this order unconditionally. Sections
with zero items for a given issue are omitted from both the TOC and the body.

**Planned improvement:** After Urgent, sort remaining sections
smallest-to-largest by item count for the current issue. Not yet implemented.

**Events (by structural type):**

1. Single Events — one-time entries with no recurring pattern
2. Hosts with Multiple Events — organizers listing several events
3. Recurring Events — programs that repeat on a schedule

### 6.7 Asset Path Normalization

All asset paths emitted into HTML `src=` or `href=` attributes must be
normalized to forward-slash URL syntax. Windows backslash paths are
invalid in HTML and will cause broken images in some email clients and
browsers.

**Required helper (both compilers):**

```python
from pathlib import Path
from urllib.parse import quote

def to_web_path(path: str | Path) -> str:
    """Convert any filesystem path to a safe HTML URL path."""
    return quote(Path(path).as_posix(), safe="/:._-")
```

This function must be called on every image path before it appears in
`src=` or `href=`. Both attributes for the same image must use the
identical output of `to_web_path()`.

**Never** pass a raw `pathlib.Path` object or a string produced by
`str(Path(...))` directly into an HTML attribute — on Windows, both
produce backslashes.

